│ THOUGHT: Now I see the issue. In `createSimpleReduction`, for `RecurKind::Add`, it calls `Builder.CreateUnaryIntrinsic(getReductionIntrinsicID(RdxKind), Src)`. The `Src` is the vector value to reduce. In    │
│ our case, `Src` should be the vector phi value, but looking at the debug output and the generated IR, it seems `Src` is `splat (i8 1)` instead of the vector phi.                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The problem appears to be in how the reduction value is obtained. In the VPlan debug output, we see `EMIT vp<%4> = compute-reduction-result ir<%conv678.i.i>, ir<%add.i.i.i>`. The operands are the reduction  │
│ phi and the add instruction. But in the generated IR, the reduction is computed on `splat (i8 1)` which comes from the add instruction being widened to a vector of ones.                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Actually, looking more carefully at the debug output for VF=2: `WIDEN ir<%add.i.i.i> = add ir<0>, ir<1>`. This widens the add instruction. `ir<0>` is likely a vector of zeros, and `ir<1>` is likely a vector │
│ of ones (from the phi). So the result is a vector of ones. Then the reduction phi is initialized with `<1, 0>` and gets updated to the widened add result (which is `splat (i8 1)`). The reduction is then     │
│ computed on the wrong value.                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The issue might be that when the add is `add i8 0, %phi`, and 0 is the identity for addition, the vectorizer should not treat this as a reduction at all. Or it should use the phi value directly instead of   │
│ creating a vector add.                                                                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Let me search for where identity values are handled in the vectorizer.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ cd /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm && grep -n "isIdentity\|getRecurrenceIdentity" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp | head -20                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                                            │
